    "day": 88,
    "title": "Being Filled With God’s Presence",
    "embed": "https://www.youtube.com/embed/j24nz-PFPoE?rel=0&list=PLcP1SVRMBQWJiPfjd2vV8pfRTtSyeQJV6",
    "content": "<div class=\"scripture-block\"><p class=\"scripture-label\">📖 Focus Scripture</p><blockquote class=\"scripture-quote\">“And be not drunk with wine, wherein is excess; but be filled with the Spirit.”<cite>Ephesians 5:18</cite></blockquote></div>\n<p>Scripture presents being filled with the Spirit as a continuous experience rather than a one-time event. The instruction is not to be filled once, but to keep being filled. This means God desires believers to live in a state of ongoing refreshment and awareness of His presence.</p>\n<p>Many believers associate God’s presence with special moments, powerful meetings, or emotional encounters. While God does meet us in those ways, His presence is not limited to them. Being filled is about daily surrender. It is learning to remain yielded so the Spirit can continually influence thoughts, attitudes, and actions.</p>\n<p>God’s presence fills what is yielded. Resistance limits fullness. Surrender increases capacity. This is why worship plays such a vital role. Worship reorients the heart toward God and opens space for His presence to rest more deeply. It is not performance. It is alignment.</p>\n<p>Being filled does not always feel dramatic. Often it is marked by quiet joy, steady peace, and increased clarity. The Spirit strengthens the inner life before empowering outward action. Fullness stabilizes the believer so they can serve without burning out.</p>\n<p>Scripture shows that the early believers were filled repeatedly. Each filling prepared them for a new phase of obedience and service. This teaches us that yesterday’s encounter cannot sustain today’s demands. Fresh filling is required for present grace.</p>\n<p>God’s presence also brings cleansing. As the Spirit fills the heart, distractions lose influence. Desires are reordered. What once competed for attention begins to fade. Fullness produces freedom because the Spirit displaces what does not belong.</p>\n<p>Being filled is not about striving harder. It is about yielding more fully. The Spirit does not force Himself into crowded hearts. He fills those who make room. When the believer stops resisting and starts welcoming, fullness flows naturally.</p>\n<p>So, ask yourself what occupies the most space in your heart. Invite the Spirit to fill every area. God is willing. His presence is abundant. The invitation is continual.</p>\n<div class=\"prayer-block\"><h4>🙏 Prayer</h4><p>Father, I invite your Spirit to fill me afresh. I yield my heart, my thoughts, and my desires to you. Displace anything that competes with your presence. Fill me with your peace, joy, and strength so I may live aligned with you. Amen.</p></div>\n<div class=\"prayer-block\"><h4>Point of Meditation</h4><p>I continually yield my heart to the Holy Spirit and live filled with God&#x27;s presence each day.</p></div>"
